y child, which is why we set knives where feet forget to look. You call it cruelty and I call it memory that lasts, but I did not come only to argue; I came to weigh the worth of your so-called shared bowl against the price of wasting even a drop. If you would debate me in the seventh alcove, we will stand where Oris carved his warnings and speak so the stone can judge us both, and I will not be moved by tears unless they can be rationed like water. Convince me that your verse does not excuse indulgence, convince me that your law does not excuse hoarding, and I will unbraid one snare for every proof you offer. Fail me, and the spiral will teach what you refused to teach, and it will do so without applause or complaint.\"}\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"M8-C1\", \"title\": \"Walk the spiral in silence and unspool the traps by resonance\", \"text\": \"You move with the pilgrim line as though you were stitched into its slow hem, counting breaths under your tongue and mapping their cadence to the tremble of each riser. At every suspect step you touch stone with your resonant calcite fork and feel for the burr of a false note, the tiny shiver that says wire waits like a held breath. Solace oil darkens your wick-brush and you wet the metal as if anointing it, easing salt-stiff coils into quiet, while your ribbon-kite tucked beneath your cloak catches the lull so even your own heart forgets to rush. When a scripture knife grins from a crack, you turn its smile into a sigh, easing it free like a splinter while whispering tally marks to lull the line behind you. The pilgrims never break their silence because you borrow it and give it back, and the decree in their quiet becomes your cover, letting fingers and thought move as one. Even the harps of the distant Wind Courts seem to wait for your nod before they breathe again, and the stone warms to your steadiness, not to your noise.\", \"outcome\": \"Three steps lose their teeth without a single gasp, and t